My name in Michan Walsh. I received a 176 on the LSAT in my only administration of the test, which is in the 99.7 percentile, through self study alone. I also achieved numerous record results on AICE/Cambridge Academy and AP scores including the highest US AICE critical thinking score in 2015. As president of the debate and math clubs, I won multiple gavels and math accolades. I work with algorithms as well, another skill which demands critical thinking.With patience and very individual attention, I am an expert in helping students improve their LSAT and other test scores by effectively and efficiently diagramming logic games, carefully breaking down the argument, question, and answer choices in logical reasoning paragraphs, and fully understanding and appreciating reading comprehension essays. My teaching strategy consists mainly of working out real LSAT test sample problems and demonstrating my thought process, clarifying any questions along the way. I am also skilled in helping students develop a set of test-taking strategies to master the test. My students have seen marked improvements in their test and assignment scores. I look forward to helping you achieve your goals! 40$/ hour by Internet

I used to struggle with math my whole life. Until I had a life-changing experience in my mid 20s that inspired me to become a doctor. At the time, I actually already owned a tutoring company! But I really struggled with math and doubted that I could ever become a doctor. So I decided to hire the best math tutors from my own company to work with me. I hired two tutors: a math and chemistry tutor. They drilled me on topics like factoring, molecular mass, and significant figures. I ended up going back to University and scoring over 100% in mathematics all the way through calc II.I have been tutoring various subjects for over a decade: writing, reading, psychology. For the last 3 years I've been tutoring mathematics. I really love math..I actually own a small tutoring company myself. I've interviewed and hired dozens and dozens of tutors. But I am happy to work with a few motivated and dedicated students. I only work with regular clients who want at least 1 hour of tutoring per week. My schedule fills up quickly, so please respond soon! Thank you. - Eric

I train students to attack the GMAT with confidence, efficiency, and purpose. Using my own original curriculum in addition to the Official Guide, I train students to apply strategies that easier to learn and more effective than anything else on the market (in my humble opinion). But you don't have to take my word for it as you do NOT pay for the first session unless you hire me for future sessions. And since I love my work, I'm friendly, professional, and take GMAT training very seriously. Training takes place online via one-on-one video conference and uses my original GMAT curriculum in conjunction with Official GMAT material. $84 per hour ($125 for each 90-minute session). 5 years with a major test-prep company, independent for 11+ years. As an expert in everything GMAT, I can confidently say that most GMAT training should focus on the Quantitative section. Do I know the Verbal inside and out? Of course. But my professional recommendation is that most Verbal should be done through self-study, simply because the Quantitative section can be so broad. Although the GMAT only tests math up to about 10th grade, every single concept ever covered from K -10 is fair game. Like "remainders" or "units digits" - all fair game.I also focus on the psychology of the GMAT, including confidence issues and time management. If you're interested in moving forward, we should chat over the phone. I'll have some questions for you as I'm sure you'll have for me. My goofy website can fill in the details of how I work and features pictures of the world's most handsome rescue animals: www.TestTrainerinc.comPlease feel free to call me at your convenience at (510) 847-9711.Just remember: I can't make you smarter, just a whole lot faster.Chicago GMAT tutor, Chicago GMAT prep courseChicago GMAT tutor, Chicago GMAT prep courseChicago GMAT tutor 60605, Chicago GMAT prep courseChicago GMAT tutor, Chicago GMAT prep courseChicago GMAT tutor, Chicago GMAT prep courseChicago GMAT tutor 60605, Chicago GMAT prep courseChicago GMAT tutor, Chicago GMAT prep courseChicago GMAT tutor, Chicago GMAT prep courseChicago GMAT tutor 60605, Chicago GMAT prep course

post_text: Hello Everyone,I am a part of a two member mentoring and tutoring team and my goal when it comes to teaching our younger generations is to share in the JOY that can be found in learning when things are taught in a fun and engaging way. We are a Mother/Son team who each have our own specialties when it comes to teaching, but between the both of us, we have every subject covered! My mom earned her master's degree in teaching a while ago and since then has had so much success connecting and helping kids find what they enjoy in the world. I am a 24 year old who studied accounting, but I was able to complete a Spanish minor as well as study psychology and mental health for years after college in order to better understand and volunteer my time with PTSD survivors. I have been working with numerous young adults as well as adolescents to help them overcome daily challenges and feel a lot more confident and comfortable in their own skin. If your son or daughter needs math, reading, writing, science, social studies... HECK, EVEN GYM CLASS TUTORING, we are able to provide it! (Just kidding about the gym class) But the amount of patience and skill that my tutoring associate and I bring to the table is hard to find sometimes. I see so many young people struggle nowadays, people my age and younger have trouble adapting to technological social pressures and fall into dark places too often because it is difficult to ask for help and to tell people how you feel especially when there's so little emotional support in place for young adults and kids struggling with new life problems as a result of changing times. Our team approach to tutoring and mentoring can be tailored to whatever needs you might have. I like to introduce nature and environmental themes into my curriculum and I always customize whatever material needs to be studied, so that it is more relatable for each student. I guarantee your son or daughter will have fun and learn something new every time they have a lesson and if they don't then its a MONEY BACK GUARANTEE. I have been providing lessons for years now and I know that my formula for success and fun works!!! The only other piece of the puzzle that is extremely important to me is building a strong work ethic, learning better communication, helping kids find motivation and joy in the small things in life that are often taken for granted nowadays. I pride myself on being a role model and a leader for the younger generations and I will always help young people find success in whatever they enjoy! PRICE IS NEGOTIABLE AND WE ARE VERY FLEXIBLE AND UNDERSTANDING! LET US KNOW WHAT GOALS YOU HAVE FOR YOUR LOVED ONE AND WE WILL MAKE IT HAPPEN. If you need an A on a math test, we got you covered. If you need someone to help guide a loved one through social obstacles, we also have you covered. Don't hesitate to reach out for any reason at all. If someone you know needs emotional support in this very instant, I will pick up the phone 99% of the time and will be there in an emergency no cost and no questions asked, I just want to do what is right for young people so that they can find some fulfillment in life and so then they can give back to society in the future so that everyone will be healthier. Thank you, I look forward to hearing from you soon!-Kevin S.

Reading programs, if done carefully, is helpful, but there is no substitute for programming.  Just like in mathematics and physics, one must read and actively practice (program) to master the subject. With sufficient programming practice, there is no need to do rote memorization of code idioms -- such things will come automatically. Programming is problem solving, and it is more similar to problem solving in math than in physics, I think. Learning programming is ideally like learning to play a musical instrument. Learning math and physics also require significant practice to by-pass rote memorization, develop speed in problem solving, and develop intuition.Getting code from the internet is not a preferred approach to programming. I rarely use code from the internet, and I almost always write completely original code to solve a problem.
